1 Introduction

â¦So far we have focused on mapping just geometries themselves; we mapped, among other things:

  • country borders (polygon geometries)

  • world rivers (line geometries)

  • the locations of ports (point geometries)

All these maps, whose main purpose is to show the locations of features, are called âreferenceâ maps.

But when we build maps in epidemiology (and in most other fields) what we really care about is not the locations themselves, but how specific attributes vary across these locations. For example: we might make maps to show:

  • the incidence of a disease across different countries;

  • the concentration of a microbe/chemical in different rivers;

  • how many travelers transit annually through different ports.

Such maps, which aim to show the spatial variability of an attribute, are called thematic maps. These thematic maps usually use reference maps as their base, but they then add color or size variation to the base geometries in order to convey qualitative or quantiative information about specific themes or attributes.

3 Thematic maps with Point geometries

3.1 Qualitative

airports <- ne_download(scale = 10,
                        type = "airports", 
                        returnclass = "sf")
## OGR data source with driver: ESRI Shapefile 
## Source: "C:\Users\avallecam\AppData\Local\Temp\RtmpKM1OFU", layer: "ne_10m_airports"
## with 893 features
## It has 40 fields
## Integer64 fields read as strings:  ne_id
ggplot(data = airports) + 
  geom_sf(aes(color = type), alpha = 0.5)

3.2 Quantitative

cholera_deaths <- read_rds(here("ch06_basic_geospatial_viz/data/cholera_deaths.rds"))

ggplot(data = cholera_deaths) + 
  geom_sf(mapping = aes(size = Count), alpha = 0.7)

Remember that under the hood, ggplot is passing the âgeometryâ column to the geometry argument. You can make this explicit with aes(geometry = geometry) . For example:

ggplot(data = cholera_deaths) + 
  geom_sf(mapping = aes(size = Count, geometry = geometry), alpha = 0.7)

4 Thematic maps with Line geometries

4.1 Qualitative

roads <-
  ne_download(scale = 10,
                category = "cultural",
                type = "roads", 
                returnclass = "sf")
## OGR data source with driver: ESRI Shapefile 
## Source: "C:\Users\avallecam\AppData\Local\Temp\RtmpKM1OFU", layer: "ne_10m_roads"
## with 56600 features
## It has 31 fields
## Integer64 fields read as strings:  scalerank question
south_am_roads <- 
  roads %>%  # filter the dataset to reduce time needed to plot
  filter(continent == "South America")

ggplot(data = south_am_roads) + 
  geom_sf(aes(color = type))

4.2 Quantitative

You can mention that it is not very common (especially for epidemiology).

Below is an example with rivers in the Sacramento basin in California US. Data from here: https://zenodo.org/record/4985219.

sacramento_rivers <- read_rds(here("ch06_basic_geospatial_viz/data/sacramento_rivers.rds"))

sacramento_rivers %>% 
  ggplot() + 
  geom_sf(aes(color = richness), size = 1)

âRichnessâ is the estimated number of fish species in each segment of the river.

5 Thematic maps with Polygon geometries

5.1 Qualitative

countries <- ne_countries(returnclass = "sf")

ggplot(data = countries) + 
  geom_sf(aes(fill = economy))

5.2 Quantitative

ggplot(data = countries) + 
  geom_sf(aes(fill = pop_est))

6 Multiple layers

So far we have been plotting single geometries.

â¦.But for most maps, you will need to provide additional contextâ¦..

This can be done by plotting multiple geometries:

E.g. for the map with world airports:

ggplot() + 
  geom_sf(data = countries) + 
  geom_sf(data = airports, aes(color = type))

For the map of south american roads:

south_am_countries <- countries %>% filter(continent == "South America")

ggplot() + 
  geom_sf(data = south_am_countries) +
  geom_sf(data = south_am_roads, aes(color = type))

You could also add a âGoogle Maps-likeâ base map with streets and buildingsâ¦.using the `annotation_map_tile()` function from ggspatial. For example, for the cholera deaths plot:

ggplot(data = cholera_deaths) + 
  annotation_map_tile(zoomin = 0) +
  geom_sf(mapping = aes(size = Count, geometry = geometry), alpha = 0.7)
